snippet.textDisplay:
The term "anti-vaxx" is a slur, that is all it is. It's akin to calling someone a NAZI (where such a person is not a member of the National Socialist Workers Party of Germany).

To make some sense of it, think of the obverse. If "anti-vaxx" is bad, therefore, "pro-vaxx" is necessarily good. This position would require that all treatments that were labelled "vaccine" must be considered to be good. But, that is a logical nonsense. Of course not all treatments that are labelled "vaccine" are good, most don't make it through R&D, and even those that do sometimes have serious problems (e.g. Swine Flu vaccine in 1974). Since it is not logical to consider all "vaccines" to be good, then the suggestion that some vaccines may not be safe and effective enough to warrant their use (especially wide spread use) is not a logically flawed position. 

A vaccine is a medical treatment, it is neither good nor evil, has no moral agency, it is just a tool. Some are effective, and in situations where a person is at risk of coming into contact with a particular disease at a time when they are susceptible to a risk of adverse medical outcome, then a person may choose to use them. For instance, now that measles and chicken pox are no longer circulating as common childhood disease, it may be rational to vaccinate against these diseases so that you don't happen to contract them later in life when they can be much more serious. But, vaccines are not inherently virtuous, they are just medications. Some medications are very safe and effective, others are not. Even medications that are not particularly safe or effective may still be useful in situations where the risk to the patient from not having them outweighs the risk of adverse effects of the medication, such as many cancer treatments (which no one in their right mind would give to a healthy person).

The key to it is choice, all medical treatment MUST be voluntary and arrived at through free, unfettered consultation with a patients chosen physician. Of course, in reality this is not always possible, but health measures must not be constructed in a way to inhibit this mechanism of action. Where there is risk, there MUST be choice.
